    // I suspect this behavior will be corrected in the future
    // Remove the target="_blank"
    $('ul.wi-affiliationList').find('a[href^="mailto:"]').each(function () {
        $(this).removeAttr('target');
    });
});

div.p:
From the point of view of their structure, comparative constructions in French are made up of five elements:
the ‘item that is compared’ or ‘comparee’;
the ‘standard of comparison’ against which (1) is compared;
the ‘quantity or quality’ which is the property on which the comparison is based;
the ‘standard marker’ which states the relationship between (2) and (3); and
the ‘degree marker’ which states to what extent (3) is present or absent in (1) in accordance with the amount of (3) in (2) (Ultan, 1972).

In addition, the term ‘espèce’ was manually added to the domain ‘zoology’. Figure 7 gives the size of the vocabulary retrieved for each scientific discipline: while biology and chemistry combined amount almost to the third of the whole vocabulary, astronomy and zoology are the two domains with the least number of terms. In total, 64% of the terms judged scientific by both annotators can be found in the domain-specific vocabulary thus formed. There are several reasons why the other terms cannot be retrieved:
they are associated with a non-scientific domain (‘science’, ‘savant’, ‘expérimentation’, ‘milieu’, etc.);
they are connected to a scientific domain not included in this study (‘géographe’ and ‘psychologie’);
they were labeled as scientific because of the context (‘combinaisons chimiques’ and ‘systèmes astronomiques’); and
they are body parts and by default excluded during the term extraction (‘main’, ‘œil’). Finally, the extracted potential comparisons and their components are reviewed manually to correct mistakes and delete figurative comparisons.
